Barack Obama receives the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth US President
American President Barack Obama comes to Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth US President in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma, the medal and a check of 1.4 million dollars for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among the peoples.
The head of the White House will arrive tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the Northwegian metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First of all, he paid a visit to the Nobel Institute, where he met for the first time ever with the five committee members who elected him from 172 people and 33 organisations in October.
The presidential couple then planned a meeting with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its climax with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the prestige prize.
He receives this as the fourth president of the United States, but only as the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already advised that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when he takes over the prize.
The President does not want to evade this issue because he knows that he is taking over the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
A few days ago, he stepped up the war effort by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gol medal, the diploma and the cheque for ten million Swedish kroner (approx. 24 million Czech kroner).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The programme of events will include a banquet with the President and his wife, at which, besides Norway's king and queen, the Prime Minister and a further 250 invited guests will be present.
Obama was very cautious about the price from the beginning.
He said, for example, that he felt that he did not fully deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that the price was not only for him, but for all those who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he pointed out that this was for him "call to action".
