Czech discovery: a substance that also works with ́stamped ́ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works with viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not have the same effect on common virus variants as one of the existing medicines.
The disease AIDS cannot yet be cured.
However, the drug composition can prolong life for patients and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus proliferation also results in the development of resistance viruses, against which no medicinal products are more effective.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, the VSHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way for dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances called metalocarborans act on the protein that is responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metalocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus proliferation in a way other than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new ́improved ́ compounds, which were prepared based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-faceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Subtle and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by the HIV protease, no mature infection virus particles would arise.
When we turn off HIV protease, we also turn off the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further modified.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in the test tube, including against their resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metalocarborans on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as with the clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants, against which the used drugs are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formation, makes the metalocarborans interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
