Vaccination against pneumococci free and voluntary
Immung against pneumococci changes the familiar from January.
It is said to be the first to be free and voluntary for families.
But voices are already reporting that compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of free vaccination against pneumococci culminate.
The medicine institute already sets the maximum prices of the vaccines, which the health insurances have to pay.
The experts are also aware of the vaccination procedure.
New vaccination
Vaccines free for August children
From January, children can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococci born on 2 August last year and later.
The condition is that they have not yet received a dose of vaccine.
Those who have already started vaccination in the last year or earlier must also pay for further vaccination themselves.
The first dose must be given between the 3rd and 5th months of life of the child.
A quarter of the families had their children vaccinated against pneumococci last year.
The parents paid 1600 kroner and more for one dose.
Vaccination of the youngest children requires four doses.
On the whole, the experts estimate that the health insurances spend 300,000 to 450,000 kroner per year for the vaccination doses.
However, they save on the treatment that children would need without vaccination.
Up to now, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all children's area vaccinations.
The compulsory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear infection, but also severe infections including meningitis and blood poisoning.
Pneumococcal infections kill up to 28 children up to 10 years of age per year in hospitals.
Outside the Czech Republic, the compulsory vaccination of children against pneumococci was introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be compulsory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
As of January, this is to be paid by the insurance companies and be voluntary.
For example, Rudolf Kalovsky, head of Nahlas, mentioned that compulsory vaccination would be better.
His association has been promoting pneumococcal vaccination in the long term.
The experts at the international conference, in which our association was involved, were not very pleased with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
That's not exactly ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we have managed to achieve this at least.
I believe that this is the way we have to go now, Kalovsky led.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococci.
At this moment we are not considering this at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sesen.
The voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, the doctors claim.
Hana Cabrnochova, Chairman of the Association of Pediatricians, admits that voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks.
If all children had been vaccinated, then one could think about the reduction in the number of re-vaccinations "In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination was started as a voluntary one," says Cabrnochova, however.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of parents to have their babies vaccinated against pneumococci next year.
Vaccination against pneumococci is also groundbreaking in the fact that it is the first vaccination to be paid by health insurance and not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend the money on prevention, thus saving them for further treatment, explains Cabrnochova.
The doctors have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, this is linked to a concern of the practical pediatricians, which concerns the purchase of vaccines.
According to the original project, the vaccines should be bought by the insurance companies and the doctors should then receive them in the same way as other vaccines issued by the state to them.
However, some MEPs feared that the insurance companies could "take the money out of health insurance".
That is why doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves and wait until the insurance companies pay them.
According to the estimates, the individual practical doctors will have to invest 40,000 kroner per month, which is a significant sum.
It won't be easy, says Cabrnochova.
