Marines were among the 6,000 who laid wreaths in Arlington
Captain De'Angello Robinson travelled seven hours by bus to place a single wreath on the grave of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other naval infantrymen who took the trip from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina to the National Cemetery in Arlington to decorate graves, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they followed.
In a few months, from where we are brought back, we could be, Robinson said about the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I'd wish someone would do the same for me, so I'm trying to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who had gathered on Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of the Arlington Cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, founded this tradition in 1992 when he and some others decided to decorate several hundred graves in the cemetery in Arlington.
It is now an 18-year-old tradition and Morrill and his wife Karen, who make this journey every year, stop in different cities along the way to carry out events dedicated to people in the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across America, which extended the event to other countries.
This year, volunteers laid more than 16,000 wreaths on the tombs at Arlington Cemetery, in areas near the Pentagon, at the tombs of the Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, at Battery Park in New York, and at the Memorial of United Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second time, the Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 for the purchase and transport of wreaths.
Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster, said that she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a deceased professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said, this is her way of returning something to those who made sacrifices.
She said that this is a small contribution to how we can support civilians in our soldiers.
It's like visiting a family grave.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, the volunteers wandered across the vast lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers had older graves from the 1st and 2nd World War and the Vietnam War as a goal, since these are not visited as often as the newer graves, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children played and couples held each other's hands as they carried the fresh pine branches to the greying tombstones.
Each round wreath was dark green with a small red bow attached to the upper part.
Section 60, which is nearby and where mainly veterans of the wars are buried in Iraq and Afghanistan, remained almost calm.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 wreaths to decorate this section, but the bleak mood of the current wars filled this area.
Individuals cried openly, others prayed, and families and friends held together in the icy air.
Some read aloud the names carved in stone, while others bowed down to small black and white maps, which had been put in the damp mud for those whose tombstones had not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who shed bitter tears in front of her son's grave.
She drove eight hours from Zanesfield, Ohio, to visit the burial site of Marine Infantry Sergeant David Shane Spicer, who fell in combat in July.
No one should ever forget why we're free... my son paid for it, she said.
"If I haven't been around for a long time, I want someone to remember him."
Contractor of the U.S. government arrested by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government arrested a U.S. government contractor who sold mobile phones and notebook computers in the country, State Department representatives said on Saturday.
The contractor, which has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc., based in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for clients such as USAID, the US Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
Consular officials from the US interest group in Havana are trying to gain access to the prisoner who was arrested on December 5.
The specific charges have not yet been published, although under Cuban law a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything under the charge of "hazard".
All so-called counterrevolutionary activities, which include light protests and critical writings, pose a risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered a serious crime.
Cuba has a growing blogger community led by popular reporter Yoani Sánchez, who often describes how she and her husband are persecuted and attacked by government officials.
Sánchez has repeatedly requested permission to leave the country to accept prices, but this has always been rejected.
The arrest of an American contractor is likely to increase tensions between the Castro brothers' Communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which had sought a "slow" rapprochement to improve relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first reported Friday night by the New York Times.
The new US policy attaches importance to the United States providing compensation if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as the release of political prisoners and the creation of more room for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and sought after products in a country where the average salary of a government employee is 15 dollars per month.
The Cuban government has only allowed ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year, and they are mainly used for sending text messages, as a 15-minute phone call would cost a day's pay.
Internet usage on the island is extremely limited.
It is accessible in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government offices, such as universities.
Cubans who want to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the press spokesperson of the U.S. representation in Havana.
Berbena said she couldn't give any more information about the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - the surrender of free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the group "Human Rights Watch", which recently produced a hard report on freedom in Cuba entitled "New Castro, same Cuba", an allusion to the appointment of Raul Castro as leader of the country that replaced the sick older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said that the defendants were very often arrested, sentenced and imprisoned within one day.
He said that any solution would probably be political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, just when both countries are moving towards more dialogue.
