The performance gap actually rose from 53 to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of the Afro-American eighth graders remained basically the same, falling at a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average score of white students was not included in the test data, as the sample size was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is also not more encouraging.
The gap separating white and black fourth graders in 2003 when the first NAEP was recorded in this district was 60 scales (262 to 202).
And even though the score reached by children of both groups has increased in this period of time, the difference has hardly decreased with now 58 points.
