A Gradual Relaxation
Incorporated in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial order introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Married couples who violate this policy have to face enormous fines -- up to their three-year salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their jobs.
Chinese state representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of natural land resources could be avoided, while human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to have an abortion.
Many couples also had sex-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude towards one-child politics.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife have been single children -- and in 2007 the tone of many harsh slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Beijing University's Department of Population Research, said that government officials recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with whom a partner is an only child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city in July to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines that describe in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent out municipal employees and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and to pass through information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice to those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not exactly encouraging, said family planning representatives.
Disappointing Response
Although officials from a rural small town in the outdoor areas of Shanghai said that there was an upswing in the applications of couples who wanted a second child after the start of the campaign, the urban districts did not report any change.
For the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, as an example, only four to five applications are received per month.
Deceived Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the expected number of births in the city in 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Shanghai Caolu Community Family Planning Committee, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to give the best to their first one, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that they were legally allowed to do so.
But, like many Chinese, they have only a small health and life insurance of the government.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we're being robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
But the problem is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for her hesitation.
Wang, the head of staff, said she only wanted a child because she was an only child. "We were the center of the family and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and do not really want to do so."
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it bluntly.
For middle-class parents with a double career, which lowers the birth rate, he said, it's about being successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The age group of 20 to 39 years old grew up to see their parents fight during the early days of the Chinese capitalist experiment and they do not want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, places huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the question of space -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and life planning -- "If the child is 9 months old, you already have to have a CV for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group drafts emission reduction plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been marked by wild poses and mutual accusations -- again focused on Friday with the publication of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrial nations shouldering the greatest burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has highlighted both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that runs out of time, as next week more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how developed and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and what should be the upper limit of the global temperature rise that policymakers would share.
The process is given great flexibility, according to John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, called "the big picture".
It shows the outline of a possible agreement in which the industrialised nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent in the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also given the talks on Friday a boost through its commitment to provide 3.6 billion US dollars per year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change, from the mastery of floods and droughts to the prevention of deforestation.
Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that the talks last week had determined.
The US Climate Special Representative Todd Stern has rejected formulations that require binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if they are not financed by the industrialised nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration is running a tougher line with China than representatives of the Bush administration less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without larger emerging economies getting up and taking action, says Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern issued his statement an hour after the statement by Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei, saying that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or was "highly irresponsible" of him saying earlier this week that the United States would not help China financially to master global warming.
Because the future economic direction of the great world powers is at stake, break lines have opened up both within the industrialised nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle is about saving individual economies as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the big powers are struggling to find out who should bear the cost of slowing down greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have gone to act more aggressively to hold the countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic dominance will develop, says Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change stated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leaders say that the talks will best lead to a political agreement.
The alliance of the small island states with 43 members presented a 24-page draft contract early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who is leading the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of the small island states is exerting "political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and demand measures from emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency when the delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues had to be resolved before the arrival of the leaders in order to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice-Minister, got off their planes and raced through the Bella Center corridors to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to stake out claims that will be negotiated during the next week.
The sheer size of the gathering -- 13,000 people go in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists do night shows in which they make fun of the countries that they think are betraying and selling themselves, and draft contracts are passed on from hand to hand instead of by e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: almost all important ministers are here now and from Wednesday 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We come to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Politics of the Organization Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
Great Britain's first 225 km/h fast train redefines Monday feeling
Monday morning at 5:13 a whistle will penetrate the darkness to announce a train departure that is a revolution in traffic in Britain.
The first high-speed commuter train in the country will travel from Ashfort, Kent, to London St. Pancras 225 km/h and cover 93 km in 38 minutes.
To Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, Dame Kelly Holmes will then board the first Javelin commuter service from London.
He hopes that the new service will eventually connect Britain to an international rail network with fast, reliable trains and connect the major conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The neglected province could become vibrant commuter cities, working hours would be radically reduced, and switching from aircraft and car to rail would reduce national carbon emissions and road congestion.
In theory, the three major parties believe in this vision.
But the many billions of British pounds needed to build a new national rail network could still slow down the inevitable planning battle and fears of environmental damage in the British high-speed railways.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company founded in January to submit a feasibility study to the government, Lord Adonis will hand over the report to the Times on December 30.
This gives it a detailed route map of the next planned stage of the high-speed rail network.
The new railway line, which will connect London with the West Midlands, will pass urban areas and places where the impact on the environment is controversial, with a five-metre travel space.
In the open ground, the plan will show the concept within a distance of 25 meters from the final track.
HS2 will also provide three options for a larger, north-facing high-speed rail network.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
The preferred option proposed is a Y-shaped route, where a single high-speed line would lead to the West Midlands.
The line would split in or near Birmingham and a branch west of the Pennines would lead to Manchester and Scotland and another to the northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would lead to Scotland.
"It seems to be the best-functioning option," said a railway insider.
After completion, the travel time between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first section, which would not be opened before 2025, would allow travellers to travel the London-Birmingham route in 49 minutes, compared to today's slightly over an hour.
The drafts would allow trains to travel at a speed of 400 km/h, making the British rail network the fastest in Europe.
The first route was planned so that 400 meters long trains with a maximum capacity of 1,100 people can travel on it.
Up to 18 trains could operate on the London-Birmingham line per hour.
This, in turn, would mean that a terminal in London would be needed to handle 20,000 travellers per hour.
Given the geographical constraints in the capital, it is expected that an existing station would be expanded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Railway experts say that only St. Pancras International or Euston have this potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether he believes this plan should be continued or not, but the lengthy public consultation and planning measures mean that a final decision will only be taken after the parliamentary elections.
But even if it sets the wheels in motion, the rail network must be built in sections.
The trains would first have to switch from high-speed lines to existing lines in the north of Birmingham, thus continuing to travel more than three hours between London and Scotland.
This is seen as a crucial key point to ensure a change from aircraft to rail, a benchmark for the rail revolution.
Taxpayers pay for mortgage for 75,000 pounds of a conservative’s orangery
Alan Duncan, the Conservative leader in the House of Commons, has charged the taxpayer thousands of pounds a year for the cost of an orangery he had built in his home in his constituency.
The party's prison spokesman, who was demoted by David Cameron because he complained that members of the House of Commons had to live "on lean rations," increased his mortgage by £75,000 to build an oak-timbered annex to his second house in Rutland.
He was allowed to charge the taxpayer the additional interest income, a sum of hundreds of pounds per month.
The leaders of the House of Commons approved the applications at the time and were not questioned by Sir Thomas Legg, who is carrying out a review of the expenses of the Members of the House of Commons. Last night Duncan said that the applications could not have been "more clean or understandable".
Duncan, one of the richest members of the House of Commons, owns a two-storey house in a village in his constituency of Rutland and Melton.
Nearby houses have achieved a purchase price of almost one million pounds (1.1 million euros).
The ground floor includes kitchen, living room and dining room, but the Fees Office, an expenditure control center of the lower house, has agreed that Duncan needs more space.
Last year he cultivated a conservatory, which is called "orangery" in the plans.
Neighbors described it as a "glass house for entertainment".
Even during a recent investigation of his previous mortgage contracts, Duncan was not invited by the Standards and Privileges Committee to comment on the increased borrowing.
The Committee acquitted him of the breach of the rules last month, following an investigation into his expenditure.
In 2004, Duncan transferred the security for a mortgage of 271,406 pounds (300,000 euros) from his London home to his constituency house, which he had bought in 1991, a year before his election as a Member of Parliament.
Documents published this week show that Duncan received approximately 1,400 pounds (1,500 euros) a month as mortgage interest by March last year.
In April, his claims increased to more than 1,800 pounds (2,000 euros) per month.
The interest rate of Duncan's RBS mortgage has not changed during this period, suggesting that the total increase served to finance the borrowing of 75,000 pounds (85,000 euros).
The normal stepless RBS mortgage rate fell from 7.94 percent in December 2007 to 4 percent in March this year, where it is still standing.
The latest documents published by the House of Commons show that Duncan continued to claim his right to 1,250 pounds (1,400 euros) per month this May.
Duncan lost his post as opposition leader in the House of Commons in September, after an undercover reporter filmed him when he said after the spending scandal that MPs would live "on lean rations."
"In essence, working for the state means living on lean rations and being treated like S*****e."
He said, "I have spent my money on my garden, and I claim a small portion, measured by what is right.
And I could have claimed all the fucking money, but I don't."
The Member of Parliament, a millionaire from his previous career as an oil wholesaler, was attacked for the first time in May because of his spending when it became clear that he had claimed thousands of pounds for his garden before he had clarified with the Fees Office that this "could be regarded as an excessive demand".
An activist, as a protest in Duncan's lawn, dug a hole in the shape of a pound mark after it became known that he had claimed 4,000 pounds (4,500 euros) over three years.
When asked about the raised mortgage last night, Duncan said, "This had been approved by the Fees Office as well as subsequently by Legg to increase the value."
He added: "There is no debate about evading and squeezing or bending the rules or anything like that.
Everything is perfectly transparent and moves strictly within the rules, is approved and everything.
