Truckers: Three marathons for an agreement to secure supplies for Christmas
After a three-week negotiation marathon, the unions of the street association and the TLF - the only employer organization that remained until the end - came to an agreement on Friday evening that put an end to the strike order and the impending severe supply shortage for Christmas.
At the signature meeting on Friday evening, the Secretary of State responsible for transport Dominique Bussereau "welcomed" the agreement which was initiated on Wednesday morning after several weeks of negotiations.
After a second night of negotiations, the negotiators separated early Friday morning in the hope that the agreement would be signed quickly in the late morning.
Even though the three employers' associations (FNTR, Unostra and OTRE) had left the meeting upsetly.
However, more than six hours passed from the beginning of the meeting at 11:00 a.m. to the conclusion of the agreement, and the agreement was not signed until 18:00 p.m.
The conflict "would have done a lot of damage to the companies" and "it was to be feared that it would affect the holidays at the end of the year", said Bussereau.
The agreement provides for a 4% wage increase for the lowest wages (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest wage groups (international transport).
The hourly rate for workers with the lowest wages thus rises from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros.
"That's not much, but we start small first," says Patrice Clos (FO).
Activists are now instructed not to block the supply centres anymore.
"However, there will probably always be some unruly people who are not satisfied with the agreement," he adds.
TLF Chairman Philippe Grillot spoke of a "good agreement", although it was "difficult to grant these wage increases in the face of international competition".
According to him, the increase is 170 euros per month for the low and 100 to 120 euros for the high wage groups.
"This agreement is based on common sense and respect for employees," said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) spoke of "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) spoke about "an acceptable compromise".
The agreement also provides for a 3% increase in travel costs and for the maintenance of the total budget for road transport in the first half of 2010, which will in particular enable the 13th monthly salary issue and the modernisation of collective agreements to be addressed.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "the reduction of taxes on employers amounting to EUR 100 million" was the subject of an amendment by the government to the 2009 bill on corrected finances, which was adopted by the National Assembly on the night of Thursday to Friday.
The government demands "an identical" vote from the Senate.
The signature of the TLF allows the agreement to apply first to the companies affiliated to the organisation and then to the entire profession in the event of extension by the Minister of Labour.
This will be the case "in the shortest time", Bussereau assures.
The opposition of employers' associations can only delay the proceedings.
The association FNTR denounced a "deceiving trade" because the 100 million euros "were already promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate as quickly as possible, but not on the basis of a joint analysis, but rather to avoid the goose eaters being upset on the approaching Christmas days, the Unostra complains.
For the Otre association, the agreement threatens "to dig a big grave for the small and medium-sized enterprises of the industry in the next 12 months".
