Turkish Constitutional Court dissolves pro-Kurdish party. Decision with serious consequences
On Friday, the Turkish Constitutional Court announced the dissolution of the pro-Kurdish main party of the country; a decision that was immediately followed by angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision threatens to make the work of the government enormously difficult, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community in order to put an end to the conflicts that have been going on for 25 years.
The "Party for a Democratic Society" (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "site for activities that are detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity", said the President of the Constitutional Court Hasim Kiliç four days after the resolution to the press.
According to Kiliç, the decision would have been taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes required to impose the dissolution. Moreover, he pointed out that 37 of the party’s leaders, including Chairman Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from political activity for a period of five years.
Furthermore, the judge announced the waiver of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, as well as the confiscation of the Party's goods.
The DTP now has 21 seats in parliament (of 550).
Before the verdict, the party leaders stated that parliamentarians would rather leave the parliament than meet like non-party parliamentarians.
The decision was followed by a case initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Turkish Federal Court Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya. He accused the DTP of following the "instructions" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many other countries regard as a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has "no connection" to the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate.
The verdict of the Constitutional Court intersperses the government, which seeks to meet the Kurdish community and propose a series of measures to strengthen the rights of the Kurds, in order to let the support of the PKK by the Kurds run out and put an end to the conflicts.
The leaders of the DTP reaffirm that a resolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in South East Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan's prison conditions had led to clashes with the police in recent weeks.
Since the court's announcement, thousands of demonstrators have gathered in front of the DTP's premises in the megacity of Diyarbakir in the southeast, which is mainly populated by Kurds.
The police used tear gas grenades and water cannons when the demonstrators started throwing Molotov cocktails and stones.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk assumed that the court's decision "will deepen despair even further".
"Turkey cannot resolve this (Kurdish, editor's note) question on the basis of a party's ban," he told the press.
The government, consisting of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
"We oppose the closing of the parties on principle.
This does not solve the problems," said energy minister Taner Yildiz.
"This decision is a torpedoing of the democratic opening promoted by the government," said political market observer Ahmet Island.
"One can obviously expect a reaction from the PKK," he adds.
On Thursday, the PKK confessed to an attack that killed seven soldiers in northern Turkey three days earlier, one of the most brutal attacks in recent months.
