The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reporting Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived some 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent of Pangaea at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the propagation and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, team member Randall Irmis reports from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some of the bones as a new species.
In the course of the excavation, they collected the remains of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This discovery is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these primal dinos is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts discuss when the lizards split into their three most important developmental lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the velociraptor and the birds, the four-legged sauropods and their relatives known as "long necks", and the plants-eating ornithischia (bird-basin saurians), which included the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus, for example.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found clues to airbags, such as the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant sauropods later also had air bags and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of both groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
According to this, the three lines of development separated early on and spread from South America over all parts of the world, which at that time formed a single land mass as a supercontinent of Pangaea.
This is supported by the fact that the team together with Tawa hallae found the remains of two other, not very closely related theropods.
The researchers argue that the three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor.
We believe there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could be distorted, because in South America many primitive dinosaur fossils have simply been preserved, while on other continents hardly anything can be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile stem to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the middle ages is still mysterious.
During the Triassic period, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flight dinosaurs, and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while the relationship died out at the border from the Triassic to the Jura.
Success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but not the other reptiles.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact caused a group of animals to bloom, which had also developed in the Triassic, and since then a shadow existence has extended: the mammals.
