Dream Worlds
Some see pictures in a awake state and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality are not only blurred in the case of the mentally ill and in the drug rush.
As long as it happens in your sleep, it's all right.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we are allowed to indulge ourselves uninhibited in the wildest imaginations and imaginations.
However, those who experience dreamlike conditions in wax, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or drug addicted in the modern Western world, at least as a stranger.
But such images and voices are not only created by the mentally ill or intoxicated with drugs.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that enable us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes make the boundaries between dream, delusion and reality blur.
Dream-like altered waking states can occur in a variety of forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic rapture states, psychosis and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the neuronal messenger substances of the brain - above all dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction of different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over him
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, stated in 1861 a "great similarity of delusion with dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was "a psychosis, with all inconsistencies, delusions, illusions of such."
It is autumn 2001 when Henning T. turns into a comic character.
His body is two-dimensional and squeaky-colored.
Gravity has no power over him, he's floating on the ceiling.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devil-figures with blood-red, distorted frays, teeth-fleshing.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar from walls and radio.
He can't stand them anymore, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. pulls two cables out of the stereo, knots them into a loop and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs on a speaker and lays the noose around his neck.
Jump.
The noose is loosening.
That's supposed to be a lesson for you, the voices scream in a drum-splashing choir, "Go to the clinic and let yourself be healed!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last one is 2 years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, he takes medications against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He's learned to live with his illness. He's been married for three years.
In psychosis, I experienced the worst fear and the deepest despair, he says.
The illusions are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric hospitals it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, those affected can no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds; they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of size, relationship or persecution.
Voice listening is particularly common - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to separate important things from the unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the floodgates for a flood of ideas and fantasies that originate from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the centre of the action, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time he gets into a passive role, he is overwhelmed by the events, like in a dream, and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A comparison of reality is usually not possible for them, the illusions are cruel reality, waking up excluded.
To have experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, is basically preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are rooted in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real context.
Why exactly our brain beats capriols still puzzles researchers.
Exceptional states can cause any human being to lose the reference to reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers assume that minimal brain damage is present in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery, how the disorder of the neural system comes about, which at first did not manifest itself over many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can trigger a psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains are hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get them, says the Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether false images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a question of the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he evaluated his findings in the book "The Irreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations belong to the typical side effects of psychosis, but also to surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's disease and cranial brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain of healthy people hallucinates.
According to Kasten, hallucinations are composed of memory contents that are usually held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain is hot, or even when stimulation is lacking.
