75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women "Fruitability and Career of Women in Spain".
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities on the labour market restricted by their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to start a family and in the number of children, depending on whether women work or not, and if so, what kind of profession they pursue.
Those of them who do not do any other work outside the house, work only part-time or do not have a fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with fixed employment, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 years of age with a permanent job are given their first child on average only 3.7 years after moving in, a figure which increases to 4.1 years for women with a permanent job, who have taken longer to achieve this and who have moved in and realized the first child much later.
In addition, the type of work has a great influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar regarding the readiness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference was also noted among women of the same age.
For example, women in the 35-49 age group, depending on whether they only have a secondary education or a higher education, became mothers for the first time, on average, at 25,1 or 32,1 respectively.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women who have completed their main degree are already getting married and having their first child before their first permanent position, the women with a middle or high school degree are doing it exactly the other way around and are first looking for a permanent position and getting married after it and then having their first child, Delgado notes.
