Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case at the time with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as is currently the case with the ESP stability control system, the auxiliary systems for braking in emergencies must become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, and a waiting period has been set for the remaining vehicles until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many rear-end collisions due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assist is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which detects the system based on the brake strength applied by the driver to the brake pedal.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not slowed down with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistance.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is expected that one in four accidents could be prevented by personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assister exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to minimise the damage.
