Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are towed to the workshops, where an expert assesses the damage and the cost of the repair.
Not a single accident is the same and the calculation of the costs of parts and working hours can be a long and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer science tools, it is a matter of minutes
That's why almost 100% of the reviewers use this type of system.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from manufacturers in order to process them afterwards and offer them to their customers in the form of a useful programme.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all expert opinions are produced with their products.
The other two companies competing with in the tool market for review and preparation of a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is far from easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Sales Manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each providing the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is increasing, to the point that more versions, variants and motorizations have been launched in the last five years than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes onto the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a laborious task, because every single one of the thousands of vehicle parts has to be catagolized and its price entered.
In addition, a "intelligent" graphic image is created of each model, on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure is proceeding quickly.
If this is a less common car, it may take up to three or four months. Currently, 99.2% of cars sold in Spain have full information about Audatex.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the vehicle park on the roads, it is over 99%.
In order to carry out the documentation work and to produce databases, Audatex has eight centres worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters are located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics experts) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information enables companies to use it in various ways, thus offering different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country there are also tools for the management of scrap parts or for the calculation of the fair value or residual value of a car.
The only company that informs about a guide who about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex offers this offer not in Spain, but in the United States.
When reviewing the products that Audatex offers, it is easy to get an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, the star of which is AudaPlus, a standard solution for assessing accidents for the reviewers.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles as well as light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid for according to the purpose, i.e. for each expert opinion.
It will be most expensive for customers who use it rarely, at most ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, any insurance company that makes thousands of expert reports negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran from the assembly line, solely on the basis of the chassis number.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle windows, and AudaSubastas is an open service on the Internet for the specialist market, with which one can offer for vehicles that have been declared as total damage.
Your statistics service is very useful in identifying trends, conducting geodemographic analyses, or for obtaining information on variations by brand and model.
For example, it can be used to examine how many models of a particular brand of car had to go to the workshop due to breakdowns or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
Among others, it distributes Gt Estimate, which is also intended for evaluators and provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer in the same way.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa group, which was founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns or maintenance of vehicles.
The GT expert opinion guide is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Their business volume has increased by 20 % annually over the last three years and in 2008 sales amounted to 10.8 million euros.
At the beginning of last year, they also started to enter the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its business is carried out in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. They work with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, including 3,000 in Spain.
Total sales in the world of the Solera group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amounted to 557 million dollars, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2 % more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was worth $1 billion on the stock exchange and today its shares are traded at a value of $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, they have been on the New York Stock Exchange and part of the Standard & Poor's reference index.
